@Rapido [τ , ⛏] what’s you view on dtao?

That's a complex topic, and I haven't fully reviewed the DTao whitepaper yet, there are many intricate parts. So, I'm not sure if I've studied the subject thoroughly enough to provide you with an objective and constructive answer.

However, based on my current understanding (please note that my opinion is tentative, and I may totally be wrong), the current risk associated with releasing Dτao lies in potentially losing many holders within our ecosystem. This is mainly due to the widespread confusion that the majority of the community is experiencing regarding τao/Dτao/Sτao/Dτao Pools, inflation formulas, and so forth. Everything seems too abstract for most people. Despite Const's efforts to present it to the community multiple times, I have no information on whether anyone has begun experimenting with it btw. As of now, I'd say that DTao is intimidating to many. Therefore, in the short and medium term, I personally believe it could lead to many instability. In my view, everyone right now (including myself) is simply afraid of losing their treasury, the hard-earned τao tokens, and possibly the future τao they're accumulating.

One noteworthy aspect is that our ecosystem is currently facing several challenges, some of which we are all aware of. Without listing them all, one of the most significant issues is the root network's centralization and the way a small number of groups can manipulate τao's inflation (emission). For this reason, I consider Dτao to be a positive innovation in the long term. Will it succeed? I cannot say, but I think it's commendable for the foundation to attempt to address these problems rather than doing nothing. Even if it means experiencing setbacks in the process.

In my opinion, a viable solution for adopting Dτao without so much fear would be to emulate what other prominent blockchains are doing. This involves setting up a dedicated testnet for it, similar to how Ethereum has Rinkeby, Goerli, Sepholia, and others.
